In the past four decades, the longtime New Yorker cartoonist Roz Chast has created a universe of spidery lines and nervous spaces, turning anxious truth-telling into an authoritative art. “I’m going to go home and review this conversation and ﬁnd every horribly embarrassing thing I’ve said for the past hour and feel mortiﬁed about it,” she said to Adam Gopnik, during an interview for this piece. But, Gopnik writes, “though her work thematizes her apprehension and anxiety, she is a woman of considerable authority, and unstinting appetites.” At the link in our bio, step inside weird and wonderful universe of Roz Chast—a universe that stands at sharp angles from the one we know; both distinctly hers and recognizably ours. Self-portrait by Roz Chast.

"Uncut Gems," the Safdie brothers' biggest-budget movie to date, is a dazzling blend of fiction and documentary. Adam Sandler, playing a Diamond District jewelry dealer who is also a compulsive gambler, brings a desperate energy to his character. Tap the link in our bio to read the full review of this new film.
